<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900830-0037</DOCNO><DOCID>900830-0037.</DOCID><HL>   Key Witness Gets Probation   In Southern Co. Inquiry</HL><DATE>08/30/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10</SO><CO>   SO</CO><IN>ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)</IN><GV>JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)</GV><LP>   ATLANTA -- Ray Howell, a key witness in a federalinvestigation of political contributions by a Southern Co.unit, was sentenced to two years' probation on contempt andtax charges.   Mr. Howell, who did graphics work for Southern'sPensacola, Fla., Gulf Power Co. unit, disappeared prior tohis scheduled appearance before a federal grand jury inAtlanta and hid for a year before surrendering last December.</LP><TEXT>   As part of his guilty plea in April, Mr. Howell agreed tocooperate in a continuing investigation into illegalpolitical contributions. The U.S. attorney's office recentlyfiled papers under seal that gave details of Mr. Howell'scooperation.   Individuals familiar with the investigation say Mr. Howellcan shed light on the roles of individuals who were involvedin the alleged political contributions scheme.   Last October, Gulf Power pleaded guilty to two felonycharges of conspiracy to make illegal political contributionsand tax evasion and paid a $500,000 fine, ending the caseagainst it. However, an investigation of the individualsinvolved continues.   Papers filed in federal court in Atlanta in the Gulf Powercase alleged that Gulf Power used Mr. Howell's DesignAssociates Inc. to funnel money to the 1988 campaign ofFlorida State Sen. W.D. Childers. Federal law bars utilityholding companies from making political contributions.</TEXT></DOC>